                                <foliation>Modern foliation in pencil. <secFol>exultans in spiritu</secFol>
                                </foliation>
                                <collation>
                                    <p>
                                        <ref target="https://vceditor.library.upenn.edu/project/65faffae5d6968000143f273/viewOnly">Viscoll collation</ref>
                                    </p>
                                    <formula>1-12(8), 13(6+2), 14(8), 15-16(6+2), 17-20(8)</formula>
                                    <p>Quires 13, 15, and 16 each consist of three bifolia to which two glued-together singletons have been added to make quires of eight leaves.</p>
                                    <catchwords>Catchwords on quire 3 and 6 and on every quire starting from no. 8.</catchwords>
                                </collation>
                            </supportDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <additions>
                            <p>
                                <locus from="SL2r" to="SL2r" scheme="folios"/>
                                <note>Centre page, in brown ink in an early modern hand: <quote>Sancti Bernhardi Sermones in Salomonis Cantica Canticorum</quote>. Below, in pencil in a modern hand: <quote>Migne 183, ep. 785 ff</quote>.</note>
                            </p>
                        </additions>
                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding contemporary="true">
                                <p>Medieval binding. Tan leather over wooden boards. 3 double raised bands and 2 endbands. Originally, 2 clasps (presumably pin clasps) and leather straps. <locus from="LCO" to="LCO" scheme="other"/> and <locus from="RCO" to="RCO" scheme="other"/>: originally 4 round corner bosses. Top left corner of <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/>: National Library book label with the current signum. <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/>, stamped in gold: the current signum, <quote>A 154</quote>.</p>
                                <p>
                                    <dimensions type="binding">
                                        <height quantity="285" unit="mm"/>
                                        <width quantity="205" unit="mm"/>
                                        <depth quantity="65" unit="mm"/>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </p>
                                <condition>Leather heavily worn. Spine renovated; original pastedowns replaced and endleaves added at a later date. Numerous wormholes. <locus from="LCO" to="LCO" scheme="other"/>: board and leather cracked and glued together; a long tear in the leather stitched together. <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/>: leather cracked; top endband missing. Clasps and straps missing. All 8 corner bosses missing. <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/>: front pastedown detached; board and binding attachments visible.</condition>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <p>The script and layout suggest a date and origin of <origPlace>
                                    <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100111">France</placeName>
                                </origPlace>, <origDate notAfter="1225" notBefore="1201">13th century, first quarter</origDate>.</p>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>Provenance unknown. The phrase <quote>in monte pav.</quote> in the owner's note on <locus from="1v" to="1v" scheme="folios"/> may possibly stand for <foreign xml:lang="la">Mons Pavonis</foreign>, i.e. <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100257">Bamberg</placeName>. The name of the church that owned the manuscript has, however, been erased.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>Acquisition date unknown, but the manuscript has been at the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100004">National Library</orgName> since at least the 17th century and is listed as no. <quote>111</quote> in Jache's catalogue of 1698 (U 122) and no. <quote>24</quote> in the catalogue of 1734 (U 125 e).</p>
                        </acquisition>
                    </history>
